===Etymology 1===
{{etymid|ja|katana}}
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=kun|かたな|alt=釖:uncommon obsolete,𫦫:rare obsolete}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=かたな|-}}. 刀 first appears in the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' of 720 {{CE}}.<ref name="KDJ2">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2}}</ref> The furigana {{m|ja|カ・タ・ナ}} for the phonetic attestation of ''katana'' only appears centuries later; however, the reading of 刀 in the ''Nihon Shoki'' and the ''{{w|Man'yoshu}}'' has been generally interpreted as identical to the reconstructed {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|sort=かたな|*katana}}.

Commonly suggested as a compound of {{compound|ja|sort=かたな|片|t1=one side|tr1=kata}} + {{m|ojp|な|tr=na||edge}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref>  This ''na'' element is spelled in monolingual Japanese sources as {{m|ja|刃||edge, blade}}, but there is no historical attestation for any ''na'' reading for this character. A comparison with {{cog|okm|ᄂᆞᆶ〮|t=blade}} and modern {{cog|ko|날}} suggests a {{der|ja|qfa-kor}} origin for this latter element. Vovin suggests an Old Korean coordinate term *xʌtʌŋ-nʌrh, due to the nature of the introduction of the specific type of single-edged sabers that are used with ''katana'', mostly introduced from Korea from the 11th century onwards.<ref>{{cite-book|last=Vovin|first=Alexander|1=2008|chapter=Shinsei no Ken to Mahō no Hire - Gengogaku to Rekishigaku no Setten|trans-chapter=Sacred Sword and Magic Scarf - A Contact of Linguistics and History|title=Kodai Higashi Ajia Kōryū no Sōgōteki Kenkyū|trans-title=Comprehensive Research on (Cultural) Interactions in Ancient East Asia|location=Kyōto|publisher=Ningen Bunka Kenkyū Kikō Kokusai Nihon Bunka Kenkyū Sentā|pages=455-468|lang=ja}}</ref> Compare {{m|ja|直刀}} ''chokutō'' for a more common reading of {{m|ja|刀||sword}} prior to the 11th century.

